As your Kubernetes configurations grow, manually editing large 
YAML files becomes error-prone and hard to maintain across 
environments (dev, staging, prod).

Templating tools help you manage Kubernetes manifests more 
effectively by reducing duplication and enabling 
environment-specific customization.

Here are the three main tools you’ll encounter:


Tool	     Style	      Best For	                   Built into kubectl?	Learning Curve
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

kustomize    Declarative      Environment-specific         Yes                  Low–Medium
             overlays         configs, GitOps              (kubectl apply -k)

helm         Go templates     Packaging, versioning,       No                   Medium
             + charts         complex apps

yq           YAML processor   Quick edits, CI/CD           No                   Low
             (like jq)        pipelines, transformations



    *  kustomize is ideal when you want to keep everything as 
       plain YAML and layer changes on top (bases + overlays).

    *  helm is better when you need a full packaging solution 
       with values files, dependencies, and release management.

    *  yq is a lightweight Swiss Army knife for inspecting and 
       modifying YAML files programmatically.

Most teams use a combination of these tools depending on the situation.

